Olympic Medal Predictions

Introduction

This was a personal project created to be presented at a project fair to students and faculty during my time at school.

The Olympic Games are the leading international sporting events where athletes from every country are given the opportunity to compete in a wide variety of disciplines to earn rewards and recognition for themselves and their country. The summer and winter Olympics are held every two years, in alternating order, in host cities that are selected years in advance. Male and female athletes compete for bronze, silver, and gold medals that reflect third, second, and first place respectively.

The Data

The Olympic Games are the leading international sporting events where athletes from every country are given the opportunity to compete in a wide variety of disciplines to earn rewards and recognition for themselves and their country. The summer and winter Olympics are held every two years, in alternating order, in host cities that are selected years in advance. Male and female athletes compete for bronze, silver, and gold medals that reflect third, second, and first place respectively.

Objective

The goal is to analyze how the socioeconomic factors in countries influence that country’s overall success at the Olympic Games, measured by their medal count. The analysis will also contain modeling to predict a country’s success in order to determine the most important socioeconomic factors to success. This analysis can give an understanding as to why some countries dominate events while others are entirely absent from medalling.

Data Cleaning

Given that the world development indicator dataset includes thousands of different indicators for each country, it is necessary to subset to a few that are relevant and widely available for the countries in the olympics dataset.

### Choose the development indicator 
Indicators <- c("SP.DYN.CDRT.IN","SP.POP.TOTL","SP.POP.GROW","EN.POP.DNST","AG.LND.TOTL.K2","NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG","NY.GDP.MKTP.CD","EN.ATM.CO2E.PC",
                "SP.DYN.CBRT.IN","SP.DYN.LE00.IN","SP.DYN.IMRT.IN","SP.RUR.TOTL","FI.RES.TOTL.CD","NE.TRD.GNFS.ZS","SP.URB.TOTL","AG.PRD.FOOD.XD")

Next

# save the countries that have participated in at least one Olympic games and the years that the Olympics have taken place

olympicyears <- paste("X",unique(olym$Year),sep="")
olympiccountries <- unique(olym$Country)

The WDI dataset is subset to include only the variables that were specified, countries that have participated in the Olympics, and years where the Olympics were held.

wdi <- filter(wid,Country.Code %in% olympiccountries)
wdi2 <- filter(wdi, Indicator.Code %in% Indicators)
wdi3 <- wdi2[,colnames(wdi2) %in% c(colnames(wdi2)[1:4],olympicyears)]
wdi3 <- wdi3[,-5]

wdilong <- gather(wdi3,Year,Value,X1964:X2014)
wdilong$Year <- substring(wdilong$Year,2)
wdilong <- wdilong[,-4]
wdifinal <- spread(wdilong,Indicator.Name,Value)

Only Olympic games held past 1964 will be used in the analysis, as many countries (specifically smaller ones) lack data in the WDI set prior to 1960. In order to judge the success of each country, a medal scoring system will be used where bronze is equal to 1 point, silver is equal to 2 points, and gold is equal to 3 points.

olym2 <- as.data.frame(olym[olym$Year %in% 1964:2020,])


medals <- olym2 %>% group_by(Country,Year) %>% dplyr::count(Medal)
medals <- medals[-c(1,2),]
medals2 <- spread(medals,Medal,n)
medals2 <- as.data.frame(medals2)
medals2[is.na(medals2)] <- 0

medals2$points <- medals2$Bronze + (2*medals2$Silver) + (3*medals2$Gold)

Finally, we can merge the Olympics and WDI datasets. The columns were also reorganized and renamed manually.

df2 <- merge(medals2,wdifinal,by.x=c("Country","Year"),by.y=c("Country.Code","Year"))
df <- df2[,c(7,1,2,3,5,4,6,8:15,18,16,17,19:23)]

colnames(df) <- c("Country","Country.Code","Year","Bronze","Silver","Gold","Points","Birth.Rate",
                  "C02.Emissions","Death.Rate","Food.Production","GDP","GDP.Growth","Land.Area","Expectancy","Population.Growth", "Infant.Mortality","Population.Density","Population","Rural.Population","Total.Reserves","Trade.Percentage","Urban.Population")
df$Year <- as.numeric(df$Year)
df[8:23] <- apply(df[,8:23],2,as.numeric)

The world development indicator dataset was still missing about 2.5% of total before merging, so these points were imputed using linear regression. Using the mice package every complete row was used to build a linear model and the missing values in the remaining rows were predicted.

### Missing values
sum(is.na(df2))/(16*657)*100

### Imputation
dfimpute <- as.matrix(df[,c(3,8:23)])
dfnew <- mice(dfimpute,method="cart")

df[,c(3,8:23)] <- complete(dfnew)

regression <- df[,7:23]

In order to find any potential sources of multicollinearity, I used a correlation plot of the predictor variables.

Lastly I wanted to determine if any transformations needed to be applied to the predictor variables. I used a boxplot of the scaled variables (centered at 0 with standard deviation of 1) to check the range and number of outliers for each variable. There were a significant amount of outliers for some of the predictor variables, so a log transformation may be useful in our analysis.

Analysis

I decided to try four different models: ridge regression, lasso regression, decision tree, and random forest. I wanted to test a few models, specifically lasso and random forest, that would drop variables if they were insignificant due to the multicollinearity we saw in the correlation plot. I also tested each model with the standardized data and the log of the standardized data. In each of the models tested, the data was split into training (80%) and testing (20%) sets. MSE was the metric used to determine the effectiveness of each model.

So, the first step is to create a second data frame with the log of our predictor variables.

###  Creation of dataset with log of predictors
dflog <- df


### For variables that have values below 0, a started log was used
for (i in 8:23){
  if(min(df[,i])==0){
    dflog[,i] <- dflog[,i] + 1
  }
  if (min(df[,i])<0){
    dflog[,i] <- dflog[,i] + abs(min(dflog[,i])) + 1
  }
}

min(dflog[,16] + abs(min(dflog[,16])) + 1)
dflog[8:23] <- log(dflog[,8:23])

df[,8:23] %>%
  gather() %>%
  ggplot(aes(value)) +  facet_wrap(~ key, scales = "free") +geom_density()

dflog[,8:23] %>%
  gather() %>%
  ggplot(aes(value)) +  facet_wrap(~ key, scales = "free") +geom_density()

regression.log <- dflog[,7:23]
summary(lm(Points~.,data=regression.log))


min(dflog$Total.Reserves <- dflog$Total.Reserves + abs(min(dflog$Total.Reserves)) + 1)

Next we can split the data into training and testing sets.

index <- sample(nrow(df),nrow(df)*.8)
traintest <- as.data.frame(cbind(df[index,7],scale(df[index,8:23])))
colnames(traintest)[1] <- "Points"
test <- as.data.frame(cbind(df[-index,7],scale(df[-index,8:23])))
colnames(test)[1] <- "Points"

X <- sparse.model.matrix(as.formula(paste("Points ~", paste(colnames(df[,8:23]),sep = "", collapse=" +"))), data = traintest)
y <- traintest$Points
Xtest <- sparse.model.matrix(as.formula(paste("Points ~", paste(colnames(df[,8:23]),sep = "", collapse=" +"))), data = test)

This chunk of code is fitting ridge and lasso models, then predicting on the test set. Five-fold cross validation was used for each model to find the optimal lambda parameter.

### Ridge
cv.ridge <- cv.glmnet(X, y, alpha = 0)
best.lam <- cv.ridge$lambda.min

ridge <- glmnet(X,y,alpha=0,lambda = best.lam)

ridge.R2 <- ridge$dev.ratio

ridge.predictions <- predict(ridge,newx=Xtest)
ridge.MSE <- MSE(ridge.predictions,test$Points)

### Lasso
cv.lasso <- cv.glmnet(X, y, alpha = 1)
best.lam2 <- cv.lasso$lambda.min

lasso <- glmnet(X,y,alpha=1,lambda = best.lam2)

lasso.R2 <- lasso$dev.ratio

lasso.predictions <- predict(lasso,newx=Xtest)
lasso.MSE <- MSE(lasso.predictions, test$Points)

### ridge regression with log
traintest2 <- as.data.frame(cbind(dflog[index,7],scale(dflog[index,8:23])))
colnames(traintest2)[1] <- "Points"
test2 <- as.data.frame(cbind(dflog[-index,7],scale(dflog[-index,8:23])))
colnames(test2)[1] <- "Points"

X2 = sparse.model.matrix(as.formula(paste("Points ~", paste(colnames(df[,8:23]),sep = "", collapse=" +"))), data = traintest2)
y2 <- traintest2$Points
Xtest2 <- sparse.model.matrix(as.formula(paste("Points ~", paste(colnames(dflog[,8:23]),sep = "", collapse=" +"))), data = test)

cv.ridge.log <- cv.glmnet(X2, y2, alpha = 0)
best.lam.log <- cv.ridge$lambda.min

ridge.log <- glmnet(X2,y2,alpha=0,lambda = best.lam)

ridge.log$dev.ratio

ridge.log.predictions <- predict(ridge.log,Xtest2)
ridge.log.MSE <- MSE(ridge.log.predictions,test2$Points)

### Lasso with logs
cv.lasso.log <- cv.glmnet(X2, y2, alpha = 1)
best.lam.log2 <- cv.ridge$lambda.min

lasso.log <- glmnet(X2,y2,alpha=1,lambda = best.lam.log2)

lasso.log$dev.ratio

lasso.log.predictions <- predict(lasso.log,Xtest2)
lasso.log.MSE <- MSE(lasso.log.predictions,test2$Points)
### Decision Tree
tree <- tree(Points~., data=traintest)
tree.cv <-cv.tree(tree,K=10)

best.size <- tree.cv$size[which.min(tree.cv$dev)]

tree.best <- prune.tree(tree,best=best.size)

tree.predictions <- predict(tree.best,test)
tree.MSE <- MSE(tree.predictions,test$Points)

### Decision Tree with log
tree.log <- tree(Points~., data=traintest2)
tree.cv.log <-cv.tree(tree.log,K=10)

best.size.log <- tree.cv.log$size[which.min(tree.cv.log$dev)]

tree.best.log <- prune.tree(tree.log,best=best.size.log)

tree.predictions.log <- predict(tree.best,test)
tree.MSE.log <- MSE(tree.predictions.log,test2$Points)
### Random Forest
rf <- randomForest(Points~.,data=traintest)
forest.predictions <- predict(rf,test)

rf.MSE <- MSE(forest.predictions,test$Points)

#### Random forest with logs
rf.log <- randomForest(Points~.,data=traintest2)
forest.predictions.log <- predict(rf.log,test2)

rf.MSE.log <- MSE(forest.predictions.log,test2$Points)

rsq <- function (x, y) cor(x, y) ^ 2
rsq(forest.predictions,test2$Points)
